body:
#283

Also changed Story.find to Story.findOne because if you clicked on a link like "/stories/google" and there was a "/stories/google-1" in the database Story.find would return both and end up sending the user to "/stories/google" then "/stories/google-1". The user would just see "/stories/google-1" since it happens so fast but you can see it in the cli.

Since only 1 result should be returned anyway (`exports.returnIndividualStory`), I figured using findOne would be appropriate.

Quick question: What Is the reason for find using regex on the Story.find?:
 `Story.find({'storyLink' : new RegExp(storyName, 'i')}, function(err, story) {`
name: freeCodeCamp

body:
Should address #277 : The tests were not catching correct color attrs for the CSS challenges.

Going forward - reason seems to be that jquery's .css() returns the _computed_ value for colors - i.e. it's running the tests using rgb(255, 0, 0) instead of "red" or hex values. It's also very picky and does want the spaces after the commas - rgb(255,0,0) does not work. (The docs used to say that you can use strings/hex; they have since been corrected.)

http://api.jquery.com/css/#css1

I also changed another test that was looking for "monospace" as the font degradation, but the instructions said to use "Serif." (Specify how fonts should degrade)

I tested them on my computer and they seemed to work just fine.

body:
I've refactored the resources.js controller to respond faster by caching the results of most of the utility functions that get id and name info for our content. 

Controllers have been refactored to separate the return from mongo from the data used further down in the functions. 

The sitemap function in resources has been heavily refactored. Returning all users from the database is a massive network request and was blocking the server. The async.js library has been used in favor of repeatedly nested callbacks to make things easier to read.

The privacy route has been restored and permanently redirects to the correct field-guide.

Minor format changes in code for readability as well as linting cleanup to unify style.

Update Make a Person bonfire for more detailed instructions, closes #336
name: freeCodeCamp

body:
The logic behind the Camper News email notifications now fits these requirements:

> - As a person who posted the story, I want to receive a notification when someone comments on it.
> - As a person who comments on a story, I want to receive a notification if someone replies to my comment.
> - As a person receiving such a notification email, I can see who commented and click a link to go directly to the story.

body:
`node seed` finished properly for me, except that it didn't exit back to my shell, so I took a look at `seed/index.js` and found that the error was that the `counter` was being compared to a variable, `offerings`, which was the length of `challenges` + 2; I tried replacing `offerings` with `challenge.length` and it worked, so maybe offerings was just a remnant of the past, but please double check so I'm not breaking anything. I've tested these changes by, instead of checking the `counter` against `challenges.length`, I checked it against `challenges.length + 1`, and it would finish all the same calls but not put me back in the shell, so just `challenges.length` should be the right amount of calls.

I also decied to do some other changes while in there:
- Removed the function's pseudo-class syntax (CapitalCamelCase and ended with a semicolon).
- Used named function instead of anonymous function in a variable; since it wasn't passed anywhere I decided to follow the same scheme as `getFilesFor()`.
- Shortened `if..else`-statement by removing unnecessary `return`.
- Incremented counter in `if..else`-statement instead of separately before, because looks.
- Added total calls to `console.log()`.
- Commented for good measure.

Oh, and I also found and abandoned `CompletionMonitor()`-function in `seed/challenge-migration.js`, so I removed it.
name: freeCodeCamp

solves #969.

regex now allows opening style elements to have whitespace before closing '>', and also the allowed attributes (type, media etc..).
I also changed the text to read 'make sure all your style elements are valid and have a closing tag', since the regex only allows the allowed attributes (see https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/style)

*explanation about the regex: matches '<style' followed by zero or more occurrences of (any amount of whitespace + an allowed attribute + '="anything"'), followed by any amount of whitespace + '>'.

Note that this regex is not perfect, and will allow any value for the attributes, and repeating of attributes (i.e <style type="kuku" type"maluku"> is matched)

body:
In [Waypoint: Create a Set of Radio Buttons](http://www.freecodecamp.com/challenges/waypoint-create-a-set-of-radio-buttons) camper can pass the challenge by specifying only one correct `name` attribute of `input` element i.e. you can pass it with this code 

``` html
<label><input type="radio" name="indoor-outdoor"> outdoor</label>
<label><input type="radio" name=""> indoor</label>
```

which is incorrect, because you need to

> Give your radio button**s** the `name` attribute of `indoor-outdoor`.

The same applies to [Waypoint: Create a Set of Checkboxes](http://www.freecodecamp.com/challenges/waypoint-create-a-set-of-checkboxes) only here value of the `name` attribute is `personality`.

---

This PR also fixes another type of [issue](https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/issues/1017). Tests allow you to pass the challenges with this code.

``` html
<label>
<input type="radio" name="indoor-outdoor">indoor
<input type="radio" name="indoor-outdoor">outdoor<label> </label></label> 
```

and the same for checkboxes. So here one `label` is nested in another but instructions of waypoints' are very clear except [Waypoint: Create a Set of Radio Buttons](http://www.freecodecamp.com/challenges/waypoint-create-a-set-of-radio-buttons)'s one. I changed

> Each of your two radio button elements should be nested in a `label` element.

to

> Each of your two radio button elements should be nested in its own `label` element.

Closes #2750.
Closes #2067.
Closes #1390.
Closes #1323.
Closes #1038.
Closes #1018.
Closes #1017.
name: freeCodeCamp

Add test cases with numbers in the string to also check for numbers.

**Bonfire:Check for Palindrome Description**

> Return `true` if the given string is a palindrome. Otherwise, return `false`. A palindrome is a word or sentence that's spelled the same way both forward and backward, ignoring **punctuation**, **case**, and **spacing**. (but not **numbers** )

Hence, added number in the test cases.

cc: @benmcmahon100 

**Punctuation:** https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Punctuation

- Replace expect with assert
- Use strictEqual for checking equality of primitive.
  - consider `assert.deepEqual(1, true); // pass (undesirable)` vs `assert.strictEqual(1, true); // fail (expected)`
- Add message to assert test cases
- Minor modification to some existing test cases
- Add test for Bonfire Check for Palindromes
  - Checks unicode characters between "`Z`" (capital Z) and "`a`" (small a)"
    such as "`\`" (back slash) as punctuation for incorrect regex `/[^A-z]/` in palindrome solution.

body:
~~~Correct the test and test message for the 'Find White Space with Regular Expressions'-waypoint so that, instead of forcing `/\s+/gi` and showing the suggested regex as `/\\s+/gi` it requires and shows `/\s+/g`. The two backslashes were probably just an accident caused by how we handle tests and multiple escapes are necessary, the `i`-flag was just unnecessary since its purpose is to ignore the case of alphabetic characters.~~~
- Remove unnecessary `i`-flag from tests and test messages, e.g. `/\s+/gi` => `/\s+/g`
- Remove dupliate backslashes from regex test messages, e.g. `/\\s+/g` => `/\s+/g`

The two backslashes were probably just an accident caused by how multiple escapes are necessary with the current way tests are handled.
The `i`-flag was just unnecessary since its purpose is to ignore the case of alphabetic characters.
name: freeCodeCamp

body:
This PR adds the ability to test out challenges in beta
without fear that they will leak to production servers.

In development all challenges will display.

In production all challenges marked 'isBeta' will be filtered out
except in the case the environmental variable `BETA` is set true,
in which case all challenges will display.

To set a single challenge as a beta challenge add the property `isBeta = true` on the challenge.

To set a whole block of challenges (A single JSON file in the challenges directory) add `isBeta = true` at the top level object.
name: freeCodeCamp

Closes #1858 

The original first test was redundant, passing it solely makes the whole HTML invalid resulting in an odd user experience where all the tests disappear.

Along the way, someone has lenient-nified the document.ready test making it such that whitespace is now allowed so I'll chip in one last bit by making the script tag more lenient, we don't have to do the same since we ask users not to modify code above / below the script element lines in other tests but this particular test, it might be good to have as students have to type in their own script element and it's common to write:

```
<script type="text/javascript">
```

especially if they come with some web programming background so I think we should allow for it, thoughts?
name: freeCodeCamp

body:
Adds the feature requested in https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/issues/1343. Looks like this: http://prntscr.com/8vvgd7, two examples of gists: https://gist.github.com/anonymous/29ee0f9a9e21d34e78eb, https://gist.github.com/anonymous/8a9f708ac77a7c002011.
A couple of words about the implementation. By clicking that "create gists" button a new blank window is opened. After that we perform an AJAX `post` request to `api.github.com/gists` with the appropriate data (`data` object). From `api.github`'s response we get the `html_url` of the newly created **anonymous** gist. Then we change the window's `location.href`.
You should notice two things:
1. These gists are anonymous because we need to get user's authentication info to make them authorized (and I've no idea how to do that). As @BerkeleyTrue said "I don’t think there is going to be a way that we can share that information with the client side" (if user's GitHub account is linked to user's FCC account).
2. The new window is going to be blank until we get the answer from `api.github.com/gists`.
This is done because the browser will normally block the window like any other pop-up. To avoid this we need to open the window immediately after the button click and do any manipulations (in this case changing `location.href`) after AJAX request.
Another way is performing a synchronous AJAX request but this will freeze the browser until GitHub's response.
Closes #1343.
name: freeCodeCamp

This forces the timestamps loaded into cal-heatmap in the profile view (account/show.jade) to morph into the timestamps they'd be if the user was sitting next to the server.

To test it to make sure everything jives you'll need to set your computer's timezone to EST otherwise the _server_ will take up your local time and then the heatmap won't match the completed list further down in the profile.

This PR closes #2290
name: freeCodeCamp

We proxy the jquery object. This lets us use the jQuery that FCC
uses in the iframe.

Since jQuery sets the context, the main document object or DOM, at script
load, we need to create a proxy with the context of the iframe,
the document object of the iframe.

This was originally set to the body element. But not all challenges
require a body element.

body:
This pr removes the dependency on web workers and handles infinite loops for/while loops. Handles most recursion loops but not perfectly. It does as good as the current implementation.

The benefit of moving away from web workers is it allows us to use whatever library in the iFrame without require to mock it in the web worker environment which has no DOM.

The drawbacks are that we can't shutdown a iframe like we could a web worker. This actually doesn't apply to use because we only used web workers in some situation, but we ran code in the main thread most of the time.

closes #4882

body:
This enhances 'Step Challenges' functionality. Currently, Step Challenges force user to click on 'Open in New Tab'. 
The improvement is that 'Open in New Tab' is not forced on users if they have completed the challenge already. The code verifies if a user has completed a challenge or not. If completed, he will have a free pass at 'Go to next Step'.

Tested in local machine. Chrome-- both for 'logged in' users and 'not logged in' users.
To test in local machine, I removed completed challenges using mongo shell.
To remove the `completedChallenges` list in your database, in order to simulate that you are doing challenge/waypoint for the first time, I followed the following steps.
- Open mongo shell `mongo shell`
- `use freecodecamp`
- `db.user.find().pretty()`
- Identify the `"username"`.
- `db.user.update({"username":__username__},{$set:{"completedChallenges":[ ]}})`

Closes #3690

body:
Hello :wave:

:rocket::rocket::rocket:

[connect-mongo](https://www.npmjs.com/package/connect-mongo) just published its new version 1.1.0, which **is not covered by your current version range**.

If this pull request passes your tests you can publish your software with the latest version of connect-mongo – otherwise use this branch to work on adaptions and fixes.

Happy fixing and merging :palm_tree:

---

The new version differs by 40 commits .
- [`2e8e6dc`](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/commit/2e8e6dca2f27d793b08df56e21e204015ef5c830) `Release v1.1.0`
- [`e99baa6`](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/commit/e99baa62cbfddbb8da157302d21cccc9971b1146) `Add support for mongodb 2.1.x`
- [`678ad6b`](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/commit/678ad6b6004bc25c9ba42c34ba5b12973e4963f3) `Release v1.0.2`
- [`11494b6`](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/commit/11494b6c73c92773841a66ba370e51cd2f852552) `Fix ES5 entry-point and add test for that`
- [`13b02ed`](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/commit/13b02ed1e1beec1d4986b680d88c225236568a13) `Fix package entry-point and release 1.0.1`
- [`7f4dcf2`](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/commit/7f4dcf294712f633495357a8d99e2f479752099c) `Fix anchor`
- [`9a1513f`](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/commit/9a1513fe5b7b212cfba822a1a4dc9bc84ccebfc6) `Update README and publish 1.0.0`
- [`da385cf`](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/commit/da385cf3f0a2e272dbf9ce45e4f7b8660751ddfc) `Bundle fallback version (ES5)`
- [`7aec528`](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/commit/7aec52888734a15bd9d249f2b3c3c36abcfc845f) `Update badges`
- [`97ab825`](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/commit/97ab825f248a6ce4014f72d18513ebc275764299) `Drop license details`
- [`d09953c`](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/commit/d09953c4a1ab8ee49c211b472fd9d03f0859932a) `Deal with legacy Node versions`
- [`d9f1433`](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/commit/d9f14339ed5fc2d7e6c87b29ab60d1f7cec1a984) `Update test and coverage tools`
- [`fcf4d8c`](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/commit/fcf4d8cdbdf7adbca6bb6783fb5b753d38fbebea) `Fix lint`
- [`4db081d`](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/commit/4db081dd02b9177e073f7d7e17d17b449ea55e07) `Make code compatible with Node.js v4`
- [`b35ecd9`](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/commit/b35ecd9f0e9dbf2b625893cafa0c2fdfbd7295f3) `Modernize code and drop some dependencies`

There are 40 commits in total. See the [full diff](https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/compare/f1f7a09fb58e27e0f5472daaf40c92f112a39f4e...2e8e6dca2f27d793b08df56e21e204015ef5c830).

body:
Closes #6028 

I added a few tests here as per @SaintPeter 's issue.

We would now be checking for any two strings being added together using the `+` operator,
a variable name `myStr` being equal to the combination of strings we want,
and that `myStr` is being created somewhere using `var myStr`.

Therefore the code 

```
var myStr;
myStr = "This is the start." + " This is the end.";
```

should now be valid.

body:
I met with @gitasong today for several hours and we pounded on some of the Basic Javascript.

There are extensive rewrites to several waypoints:
- Comment Your JavaScript Code
- Declare JavaScript Variables
- Understanding Boolean Values - Moved much later in the curriculum
- Comparison with the Equality Operator
- Use Conditional Logic with If Statements - New tests, too
  ![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/553494/12225315/2b4c7732-b7bd-11e5-8a52-002a84219d08.png)

These changes are to simplify/explain better some key enabling concepts.  They're part some larger rewrite work I plan on doing to fill in some gaps.

I also changed the background color of the code block to be a nice yellow.
name: freeCodeCamp

Adds the following buttons to the Gitter tool pallet.
![](http://i.imgur.com/i3d6r9g.png)

Clicking the second button copies the challenge code in Markdown syntax.

This PR refactors and normalizes the endpoint and the ajax request.
Some weird bug keeps popping up on the server, but keymetrics has
decided to take a crap and not actually report back with the error
I don't know what exactly is causing it.

Normally I don't like fixing something I can't see, but I'm getting
a constant flood of emails because of some obscure bug here.

We removed the `completedWith` functionality a while back so that
was removed from this endpoint and the ajax call.

To test, verify that you can complete both a zipline/basejump.

Also show last updated date since it is possible a user might want
to update links

body:
Some browsers have issues detecting exact font and image sizes when zoomed
in or out.  Prior workarounds have failed and we don't want to use regular
expressions, which have many defeciencies.

For the short term we will add a note to the affected challenges that the
browser zoom must be at 100%.

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/553494/12531536/371caf2e-c1b2-11e5-9460-9bf42be13fe7.png)

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/553494/12531539/3cfa67c4-c1b2-11e5-8d61-e888518fd9ee.png)

body:
For Google Analytics to be meaningful we need to be able to track not only the challenge that has been completed, but which "version" of a challenge is being completed.

To that end I have added a check-sum calculation to the `node seed` process.  What this does is generates a 32 bit check-sum (using Adler's method) for the textual sum of the Title, Description, Challenge Seed, and Tests elements.  This check-sum is written to the database at seed time. (It's also calculated when a challenge is loaded from disk).

When information is sent to Google Analytics the check-sum is appended to the name of the challenge, separated by a tilde. It looks like:
`challenge-name~32165468`
This allows the check-sum to be easily extracted from the title with a simple split operation, as needed.
## Testing

I have tested locally to the extent that I can see that the check-sum is calculated and sent to GA, but I don't have an account set up, so I don't know what it looks like on the receiving end.

We should probably test on beta to make sure it gives the data we want.

Mostly I'm looking for feedback.  I think this may work "as is", but it probably needs extensive testing.  
## Longer Term

The great thing about this lightweight check-sum is that we can easily calculate it for any given commit and trace changes in specific challenges back to a specific version of the challenge.  I've got a script which does some of that already, just need to get it to go back in time.

Addresses some aspects of issue #5405.

Still more to do.
name: freeCodeCamp

body:
New function to prepare timestamps for streak calculation was added: it converts all timestamps to start of the day (in given timezone) and filters to distinct days. Tests added for this new function.
Unique days are being sorted only once (instead of twice): current streak calculation is done from right to left, longest streak - from left to right.
Current streak calculation changed to return after current streak is found. 
In unit tests date faking added for `new Date()` or `moment()` to return fixed date all the time. Tests become none time specific.

body:
GitHub and CodePen changed their on-boarding, so I created new gifs and instructions to reflect this. 

I also moved some awkward br elements from challenge descriptions.

I also added special copy that told people who already had GitHub / CodePen accounts how to proceed, and an explanation for why we don't have a skip button (since that is a feature we don't want to implement because people will compulsively click it and we'll spend all day manually telling people how to set up GitHub accounts, etc.)

The wiki has changed significantly. I don't think we need the wiki challenge any more.

I gave the tribute project a creation date so it will be marked as new.

I also removed the jQuery examples from the CodePen onboarding flow, since campers won't have completed jQuery by the time they reach that.

body:
It's not accurate to call the `assignment operator` `=` an `equal` operator, since it might be confused with the `equality operators`, eg `==`.

For the very same reason changed the `Minus Equals` wording to characters `-=` and titled the challenges with its commonly used name: compound or augment assignment (see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augmented_assignment)

What do you think of this clarification?

Thanks.
name: freeCodeCamp

Removing react-bootstrap component Row from Hikes.jsx and Hike.jsx as it adds a row class which broadens the margins making it unresponsive for mobile. Now using just a div in Hikes.jsx and a col-xs-12 in Hike.jsx to render video challenges. Galaxy S5, Nexus 5X, Nexus 5P, iPhone 5, iPhone 6, iPhone 6 Plus, iPad

Addresses [issue 7085](https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/issues/7085) in parallel with [PR 7688](https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/pull/7688).

7688 in parallel with this pr should close 7085. Tests 'npm run test-challenge' all pass.

Files changed:
seed/challenges/01-front-end-development-certification/basic-javascript.json

Challenges and functions changed:

| Challenge name | Old | New |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Convert Celsius to Fahrenheit | convert | convertToF |
| Write Reusable JavaScript with Functions | ourFunction | reusableFunction |
| Passing Values to Functions with Arguments | ourFunction | functionWithArgs |
| Local Scope and Functions | myFunction | myLocalScope |
| Global vs. Local Scope in Functions | myFunction | myOutfit |
| Assignment with a Returned Value | process | processArg |
| Stand in Line | queue | nextInLine |
| Use Conditional Logic with If Statements | myFunction | trueOrFalse |
| Comparison with the Equality Operator | myTest | testEqual |
| Comparison with the Strict Equality Operator | myTest | testStrict |
| Comparison with the Inequality Operator | myTest | testNotEqual |
| Comparison with the Strict Inequality Operator | myTest | testStrictNotEqual |
| Comparison with the Greater Than Operator | myTest | testGreaterThan |
| Comparison with the Greater Than Or Equal To Operator | myTest | testGreaterOrEqual |
| Comparison with the Less Than Operator | myTest | testLessThan |
| Comparison with the Less Than Or Equal To Operator | myTest | testLessOrEqual |
| Comparisons with the Logical And Operator | myTest | testLogicalAnd |
| Comparisons with the Logical Or Operator | myTest | testLogicalOr |
| Introducing Else Statements | myTest | testElse |
| Introducing Else If Statements | myTest | testElseIf |
| Logical Order in If Else Statements | myTest | orderMyLogic |
| Chaining If Else Statements | myTest | testSize |
| Selecting from many options with Switch Statements | myTest | caseInSwitch |
| Adding a default option in Switch statements | myTest | switchOfStuff |
| Multiple Identical Options in Switch Statements | myTest | sequentialSizes |
| Replacing If Else Chains with Switch | myTest | chainToSwitch |
| Record Collection | update | updateRecords |
| Profile Lookup | lookUp | lookUpProfile |
| Generate Random Fractions with JavaScript | myFunction | randomFraction |
| Generate Random Whole Numbers with JavaScript | myFunction | randomWholeNum |
| Generate Random Whole Numbers within a Range | ourFunction | randomRange |

#### Type of Change

- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds functionality)
- [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would cause existing functionality to change)
- [ ] Add new translation (feature adding new translations)

Closes #8109 
#### Description

When the iframe requests the `HTTPS://freecodecamp.github.io/wiki/en/python` page, it redirects to `HTTP://freecodecamp.github.io/wiki/en/python/` which, because it's a HTTP, gets blocked.

This adds a trailing slash to the iframe source if one doesn't exist already so that the page never redirects in the first place.

Hello :wave:

:rocket::rocket::rocket:

[helmet](https://www.npmjs.com/package/helmet) just published its new version 2.0.0, which **is not covered by your current version range**.

If this pull request passes your tests you can publish your software with the latest version of helmet – otherwise use this branch to work on adaptions and fixes.

Happy fixing and merging :palm_tree:

If this pull request passes your tests you can publish your software with the latest version of react – otherwise use this branch to work on adaptions and fixes. Happy fixing and merging :palm_tree: --- [GitHub Release](https://github.com/facebook/react/releases/tag/v15.0.2)

React

  • Removed extraneous files from npm package. (@gaearon in #6388)
  • Ensure componentWillUnmount is only called once. (@jimfb in #6613)

ReactDOM

  • Fixed bug resulting in disabled buttons responding to mouse events in IE. (@nhunzaker in #6215)
  • Ensure <option>s are correctly selected when inside <optgroup>. (@trevorsmith in #6442)
  • Restore support for rendering into a shadow root. (@Wildhoney in #6462)
  • Ensure nested <body> elements are caught when warning for invalid markup. (@keyanzhang in #6469)
  • Improve warning when encountering multiple elements with the same key. (@hkal in #6500)

React TestUtils Add-on

  • Ensure that functional components do not have an owner. (@gaearon in #6362)
  • Handle invalid arguments to scryRenderedDOMComponentsWithClass better. (@ipeters90 in #6529)

React Perf Add-on

  • Ignore DOM operations that occur outside the batch operation. (@gaearon in #6516)

React Native Renderer

  • These files are now shipped inside the React npm package. They have no impact on React core or ReactDOM.

#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

Added functionality to the Wiki button in the navbar. Also added a button to the challenge complete modal.

If you are on a challenge that is of type HTML, JS, or Bonfire, clicking the Wiki button in the navbar or the new button in the challenge completion modal will take you to the appropriate challenge page that often has a solution.

Clicking one of these buttons while not on an HTML, JS, or Bonfire challenge will take you to the wiki homepage, as specific pages for these challenges and steps often do not exist.

Known issue:
There are some challenges (I've found 5 so far) that do not have a corresponding wiki page and thus bring up a 404 in the wiki pane.

closes #8108

body:
Hello :wave:

:rocket::rocket::rocket:

[babel-plugin-add-module-exports](https://www.npmjs.com/package/babel-plugin-add-module-exports) just published its new version 0.2.0, which **is not covered by your current version range**.

If this pull request passes your tests you can publish your software with the latest version of babel-plugin-add-module-exports – otherwise use this branch to work on adaptions and fixes.

Happy fixing and merging :palm_tree:

---

The new version differs by 26 commits .
- [`cf8cedd`](https://github.com/59naga/babel-plugin-add-module-exports/commit/cf8cedd239ebce774536fe7baec732a3b405c298) `0.2.0`
- [`a07c274`](https://github.com/59naga/babel-plugin-add-module-exports/commit/a07c2747e59b04cd0b0a4862f903e617b5a7612e) `perf: use`template`argument property instead of`babel-template``
- [`d1922e6`](https://github.com/59naga/babel-plugin-add-module-exports/commit/d1922e66cef0f1ad16b4e00829e7b379015af747) `Add node-v6 in TravisCI :tada:`
- [`fe69568`](https://github.com/59naga/babel-plugin-add-module-exports/commit/fe69568dbbd03d7ac93d52eb8b495d2a5a624417) `docs(CHANGELOG): change date format to ISO 8601 [skip ci]`
- [`f8d4a50`](https://github.com/59naga/babel-plugin-add-module-exports/commit/f8d4a507209403f4e60d73de93a4824c13b54240) `0.1.4`
- [`8c39825`](https://github.com/59naga/babel-plugin-add-module-exports/commit/8c39825bd2e360463179a428951fd1061d7f106a) `Merge pull request #33 from 59naga/patch-1`
- [`ae8b254`](https://github.com/59naga/babel-plugin-add-module-exports/commit/ae8b254037dc3b839cf110711afe6c3c189c211e) `chore: tweaks version/postversion`
- [`8471534`](https://github.com/59naga/babel-plugin-add-module-exports/commit/8471534665bf90e2bdb43cb028912cbd5383c5f7) `Fix #31`
- [`83d975c`](https://github.com/59naga/babel-plugin-add-module-exports/commit/83d975c4581b35816e303c6c5de4221147b43543) `Remove unnecessary`lodash.get``
- [`50253c8`](https://github.com/59naga/babel-plugin-add-module-exports/commit/50253c83cd117ebe1218d2e94e9e69729cf8fde1) `Tweaks changelog.js/CHANGELOG.md [skip ci]`
- [`e90ed8e`](https://github.com/59naga/babel-plugin-add-module-exports/commit/e90ed8e8f5f71a465dfd07e35861d456b503d1e0) `0.1.3`
- [`29b883a`](https://github.com/59naga/babel-plugin-add-module-exports/commit/29b883ae0f99ef5ce9b58220900103c1edc1d5d0) `Add changelog.js for CHANGELOG.md [skip ci]`
- [`0303039`](https://github.com/59naga/babel-plugin-add-module-exports/commit/0303039c4d429245db2d6e9eacc2d4a9a8d365fa) `Fix #30`
- [`af19297`](https://github.com/59naga/babel-plugin-add-module-exports/commit/af192976a03242833a811167931a2f8a0c12dcff) `Add .npmignore for`npm publish``
- [`3d14024`](https://github.com/59naga/babel-plugin-add-module-exports/commit/3d140241f6bd91e5725525c5e37b4c6bd3fbed50) `Merge pull request #29 from 59naga/5to6`

- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [x] Closes currently open issue (e.g. `Closes #XXXX`): Closes  #8524
#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

Issue #8524 reports that `padding: 5px` needed adding the the paragraph at the top of the map menu. In actual fact, the `.mapWrapper` was set to `position: absolute` causing the map menu contents to be shifted over to the right. Removing this property (so it will be set back to the browser default of static) re-aligns the menu & removes the issue from the map content. It also allows the accordion to span the width of the container.

_Note_: This fix goes hand in hand with line 143 of maps.less - the position property of `.map-accordion` has already been set to `relative` on the staging branch (live site is currently set to `position: absolute`). So once this fix along with the fix on line 143 is pushed, it should all sit properly again.

Tested this fix using Chrome Dev Tools with the Nexus 6P, Neuxs 5X and Galaxy S5.

![fcc-map-issue-before](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/9949268/15120881/ba800e72-160f-11e6-8d0e-1094cfc33e5f.png)

_After_
![fcc-map-issue-after](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/9949268/15120914/eadebc44-160f-11e6-9ec2-c49f3e24f4ee.png)

#### Description

using `button` instead of `div`, `div` can be styled to look like a `button`, but it does not behave as a `button` semantically, for example receiving focus, respect the `tab` order, trigger `click` event when `space` is pressed. Above all, for assistive technology, `div` will never be presented or read out as `button`. A visually challenged user will never know about those `CTA`s

fixed #8575

#### Checklist:

- [x] Closes currently open issue: Closes #8590
#### Description

using `button` instead of `div`, `div` can be styled to look like a `button`, but it does not behave as a `button` semantically, for example receiving focus, respect the `tab` order, trigger `click` event when `space` is pressed. Above all, for assistive technology, `div` will never be presented or read out as `button`. A visually challenged user will never know about those `CTA`s

![a11y-button](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/949380/15234412/69a1bc72-1866-11e6-9fb6-6ebe47a05a88.gif)

- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds new functionality)
- [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would change existing functionality)

<!-- Go over all points below, and put an `x` in all the boxes that apply. -->

- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [x] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #8565
#### Description

Updated tests regex 

**Earlier** test regex was looking for 'Math.random \* 10' with parentheses like '(Math.random \* 10)' which was causing the tests to not pass when 'Math.random \* 10' was used without parentheses e.g. - aliasing it with a variable e.g - 'var random = Math.random \* 10;' 

As a fix, Removed the condition of presence of parentheses around 'Math.random \* 10' .

body:
Hello :wave:

:rocket::rocket::rocket:

[loopback-connector-mongodb](https://www.npmjs.com/package/loopback-connector-mongodb) just published its new version 1.15.2, which **is not covered by your current version range**.

If this pull request passes your tests you can publish your software with the latest version of loopback-connector-mongodb – otherwise use this branch to work on adaptions and fixes.

Happy fixing and merging :palm_tree:

---

The new version differs by 53 commits .
- [`7c717e4`](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/commit/7c717e4446f08210dec628295049835f9206a977) `1.15.2`
- [`5665038`](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/commit/566503842f2c5d80b6bd40f8e7002b3b8859aba0) `Merge pull request #244 from beeman/unmet-peer-dependency`
- [`6eb89bd`](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/commit/6eb89bde84ad50a0bab9f981e1e539ddf7e6a2cc) `Update "mongodb" dependency to caret notation`
- [`2839c0c`](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/commit/2839c0c2ae9c7a5052310668ea36341f03251601) `1.15.1`
- [`175e581`](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/commit/175e581d02e72ee4449317d09e60e6201ed26b02) `insert/update copyrights`
- [`304537f`](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/commit/304537f31b998b651ec6f71c7b84123aaab5fa27) `relicense as MIT only`
- [`d2d15da`](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/commit/d2d15dacf26e8881aa92aec9331ca88ed0d616ca) `1.15.0`
- [`21fee2c`](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/commit/21fee2ca041acad26f02753461a5df0c8ad1ecb5) `Merge pull request #241 from strongloop/feature/lazy-connect`
- [`f73ee5b`](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/commit/f73ee5b58ec08453e14e4d729fa36e5782e8ed2b) `Lazy connect when booting app`
- [`3ad7aea`](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/commit/3ad7aea2a5ab6ad03b96889b0323740cc8f371e1) `Merge pull request #68 from timosaikkonen/feature/geo`
- [`8112ebc`](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/commit/8112ebc720c4dbb74b72db3e44260905ed25128c) `Add support for geoNear queries`
- [`b2961bb`](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/commit/b2961bb776983861331060982a2387cdc7c1e735) `Merge pull request #240 from strongloop/feature/eslint`
- [`21ccb14`](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/commit/21ccb14b9d6af3564246933c33f10126abdb4f1e) `Fix linting errors`
- [`8cbdea1`](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/commit/8cbdea1849584f08375243a580196c68aa42eeef) `Auto-update by eslint --fix`
- [`bd2219e`](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/commit/bd2219e532cc3d507a477f5e17700db816af5ecb) `Add eslint infrastructure`

There are 53 commits in total. See the [full diff](https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-connector-mongodb/compare/a5febf134acecfbe4dbaa632e8a2ea5a5f6409dd...7c717e4446f08210dec628295049835f9206a977).

body:
Hello :wave:

:rocket::rocket::rocket:

[pmx](https://www.npmjs.com/package/pmx) just published its new version 0.6.2, which **is not covered by your current version range**.

If this pull request passes your tests you can publish your software with the latest version of pmx – otherwise use this branch to work on adaptions and fixes.

Happy fixing and merging :palm_tree:

---

The new version differs by 54 commits .
- [`48fe76f`](https://github.com/keymetrics/pmx/commit/48fe76f6bc41cfd1d0219869b04baa1de30f7419) `0.6.2`
- [`f3fb98f`](https://github.com/keymetrics/pmx/commit/f3fb98f3d809671fb197ddcfc27cc1c83d2bbae6) `#68`
- [`5004be8`](https://github.com/keymetrics/pmx/commit/5004be89d2c5e99f2bd7fb8feffdc8f569c11615) `Merge pull request #67 from nickclaw/master`
- [`b2515c5`](https://github.com/keymetrics/pmx/commit/b2515c574166eb442657b465e3ed4b0b51c704da) `Add test for #67`
- [`57a452e`](https://github.com/keymetrics/pmx/commit/57a452efa99f3cd933f7040f1c12260f64936759) `skip one test`
- [`e58124d`](https://github.com/keymetrics/pmx/commit/e58124d3acdd3af6104dc047f16f8796b4774b22) `refactored alert tests`
- [`a81f708`](https://github.com/keymetrics/pmx/commit/a81f708153cded86d56603b1215150ec996db03b) `refactored tests for probe alert`
- [`5d0dc68`](https://github.com/keymetrics/pmx/commit/5d0dc6879680d1f521d42bfe0640f599fc3bb743) `build all branches + test with node 6`
- [`ab18141`](https://github.com/keymetrics/pmx/commit/ab181418c81fe26c9152ac2824ec6dc2ea015105) `Added null check for alert probes`
- [`1fb33f4`](https://github.com/keymetrics/pmx/commit/1fb33f4d76c2a5e0c2d684e4d07882d9dba5c71b) `Stop clearing main module's paths`
- [`7379687`](https://github.com/keymetrics/pmx/commit/7379687d8f5f68fee5562bc73a3a00c47abaa8a5) `Added xeon test module`

<!-- All points should be checked, otherwise, read the CONTRIBUTING guidelines from above-->

<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask. We're here to help! -->
- [X] Your pull request targets the `staging` branch of FreeCodeCamp.
- [X] Branch starts with either `fix/`, `feature/`, or `translate/` (e.g. `fix/signin-issue`)
- [X] You have only one commit (if not, [squash](https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/wiki/git-rebase#squashing-multiple-commits-into-one) them into one commit).
- [X] All new and existing tests pass the command `npm run test-challenges`. Use `git commit --amend` to amend any fixes.
#### Type of Change

<!-- What type of change does your code introduce? Put an `x` in the box that applies. -->
- [ ] Small bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue)
- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds new functionality)
- [X] Breaking change (fix or feature that would change existing functionality)
- [ ] Add new translation (feature adding new translations)
#### Checklist:

<!-- Go over all points below, and put an `x` in all the boxes that apply. -->

<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask in the Help Contributors room linked above. We're here to help! -->
- [X] Tested changes locally.
- [X] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #8722
#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

The challenge "Show Relationships with a Force Directed Graph" asks campers to build a force directed graph based off relationships derived from the Camper News Feed. The Camper News Feed was recently removed, breaking existing solutions to the challenge.
This pull request replaces the challenge with a new one based on a dataset hosted on github.
The new challenge, "Show National Contiguity with a Force Directed Graph", uses countries as nodes, and these nodes are linked if the countries share a national border. The flag icons are loaded from a spritesheet generated at https://www.flag-sprites.com/. The dataset, hosted at https://github.com/DealPete/forceDirected, was adapted from a dataset downloaded from the Correlates of War Project (http://www.correlatesofwar.org/).
No libraries other than d3 were used.

Currently, the `mongod` command does not work due to an incorrect alias in the `~./bashrc_aliases` file on the current C9.io image. The staff at C9 posted a solution to fix this, but it had not been added to FCC at present.

Add test to make sure user doesn't use ES2015's `.endsWith()` method to solve the challenge.

I couldn't come up with a better test message. I wanted to be transparent on what the test is actually testing (as with any test) but if I wrote it anyway else, I felt like people might question and be confused by the vagueness of the message. If anyone has a better test message, I'm open to ideas.

#### Description

Existing exercise checks for `$('#target3').addClass("fadeOut");` code written by user to match regex `/\\$\\(.#target3.\\)/g`. 
This becomes a problem when user writes correct code `$( '#target3' ).addClass("fadeOut");` - please note the space introduced and regex fails to match. The new regex `/\\$\\(\\s*.#target3.\\s*\\)/g` introduces checks for optional spaces. So now, `$( '#target3' ).addClass("fadeOut");` with spaces around selectors is no longer a problem. Optional spaces regex ensures it matches even when when user writes code without spaces around selectors.

body: #### Pre-Submission Checklist - [x] Your pull request targets the `staging` branch of FreeCodeCamp. - [x] Branch starts with either `fix/`, `feature/`, or `translate/` (e.g. `fix/signin-issue`) - [x] You have only one commit (if not, [squash](https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/wiki/git-rebase#squashing-multiple-commits-into-one) them into one commit). - [x] All new and existing tests pass the command `npm run test-challenges`. Use `git commit --amend` to amend any fixes. #### Type of Change - [x] Small bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue) - [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds new functionality) - [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would change existing functionality) - [ ] Add new translation (feature adding new translations) #### Checklist: - [x] Tested changes locally. - [x] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #8970 #### Description **Problem:** In challenge record collection, like in #8970, almost every time, a user will get confused because they will follow instructions and write a line of code `collection[id][prop].push(value);` that is correct solution for the moment but will fail 2nd test. It fails 2nd test because while pushing a `track` to `tracks` property, `tracks` needs to exist and should be an array. This concept is not discussed at all in instructions and so comes as a surprise to the user. **Solution:** We add an instruction: ``` If \"tracks\" is non-existent before you update it, create an empty array before pushing a track to it. ``` This instruction should work as a food for thought and help deserving candidates to complete the challenge with this hint.
name: freeCodeCamp

Further, for the title Record Collection: I revised the instructions from line 4502 to line 4506 in order to disambiguate the meaning of key from the meaning of property. I added to the notes from line 4510 to line 4511 to provide a link to MDN which explains the push method. This change at first DID break the functionality of the existing published code when I tested it. So I changed line 4542 from var collectionCopy = JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(collection)); to var collectionCopy = JSON.stringify(collection);.

- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds new functionality)

<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask in the Help Contributors room linked above. We're here to help! -->
- [X] Tested changes locally.
- [X] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #8526
#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

This is the first in a number of challenges that ask the user to create a function containing a "console.log" statement. To print the output from console.log to the output area, the console.log function must be captured and temporarily replaced by a custom function that outputs to the output area in addition to the user's dev console.
For this challenge, console.log is captured after the code is run (by code placed in the "tail" area), and the user's function is run a second time to display the console.log output in the output area. The strange behavior observed which prompted this issue is due to the user's function being run without any arguments.
It is easier to simply capture console.log in the "head", and uncapture it in the "tail", only running the function once. This is what is done in subsequent challenges, and I have modified this challenge to work like the others.
name: freeCodeCamp

#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

This is the only string that will pass the challenge whereby the spaces or lack thereof needs to be precisely this:

``` js
var myStr = "Here is a backslash: \\.\n\t\tHere is a new line with two tabs.";
```

**Add code tags into table**

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2754821/16175696/1fc27296-35ac-11e6-9b0c-311902ad9d06.png)

**Rewrite instructions for more applicable coding test**

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2754821/16175697/2f170072-35ac-11e6-9d11-abb231f3186f.png)

The text underneath the first code block made is a bit verbose. However, I wanted to be clear on the strictness of the spaces because in contrast, the current challenge is specific about having spaces between escape sequences.

I made the quoted text in quote rather than in a blockquote or code tags because I wanted to differentiate the escape sequence words from the rest of the text. I refer to the text as text and not a string to hopefully not confuse campers on needing to actually include quotations in their string.

**Add more tests to be more specific on what you need to pass**

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2754821/16175699/3700f25c-35ac-11e6-8e54-e55627bc4935.png)

#### Pre-Submission Checklist

<!-- Go over all points below, and put an `x` in all the boxes that apply. -->

<!-- All points should be checked, otherwise, read the CONTRIBUTING guidelines from above-->

<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask. We're here to help! -->
- [x] Your pull request targets the `staging` branch of FreeCodeCamp.
- [x] Branch starts with either `fix/`, `feature/`, or `translate/` (e.g. `fix/signin-issue`)
- [x] You have only one commit (if not, [squash](https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/wiki/git-rebase#squashing-multiple-commits-into-one) them into one commit).
- [x] All new and existing tests pass the command `npm run test-challenges`. Use `git commit --amend` to amend any fixes.
#### Type of Change

<!-- What type of change does your code introduce? Put an `x` in the box that applies. -->
- [x] Small bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue)
- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds new functionality)
- [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would change existing functionality)
- [ ] Add new translation (feature adding new translations)
#### Checklist:

<!-- Go over all points below, and put an `x` in all the boxes that apply. -->

<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask in the Help Contributors room linked above. We're here to help! -->
- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [x] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #9185
#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

In its current form, the instructions column in the challenges with a 2-column layout change from col-md-4 to col-lg-3 at 1200px. But this means that at a standard laptop width of 1280px, the instructions column is just 25% of the total width. So often I have to horizontally scroll to see code examples. I changed col-lg-3 to col-lg-4 (and col-lg-9 to col-lg-8 for the right-hand column), to widen the instructions column and avoid horizontal scrolling.

The only side-effect I can think of is that at very wide widths of maybe 1900+px, the instructions column might get rather wide, so some sort of max-width setting might make sense if you don't have one already, e.g. 1600px?
name: freeCodeCamp

Found that if there was a syntax error in campers code, the test suite would `fadeOut`, but not `fadeIn` again. This left campers thinking the `Run tests` button was not working.

This fix is to allow some functionality while this bug exists.

body:
The instructions were originally "Access the myStorage object to retrieve the contents of the glove box. Use bracket notation for properties with a space in their name." These were somewhat unclear.

They were updated to "Access the myStorage object and assign the contents of the glove box property to the gloveBoxContents variable. Use bracket notation for properties with a space in their name" to offer more clarity to the reader.

This has been tested locally. All tests passed.

closes #9473

- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds new functionality)

<!-- Go over all points below, and after creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->

<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask in the Help Contributors room linked above. We're here to help! -->
- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [x] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #6834
#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

**Challenge**: [Iterate Through an Array with a For Loop](https://www.freecodecamp.com/challenges/iterate-through-an-array-with-a-for-loop)

Relax test regex to accept the following three correct, but different ways to initialize `total = 0`.
- Within `for` loop after the index initialization

``` js
for (var i = 0, total = 0; i < myArr.length; i++) {
  total += myArr[i];
}
```
- Within `for` loop before the index initialization

``` js
for (var total = 0, i = 0; i < myArr.length; i++) {
  total += myArr[i];
}
```
- Before the `for` loop

``` js
var total = 0;
for (var i = 0; i < myArr.length; i++) {
  total += myArr[i];
}
```

To do so, I relaxed the regex looking for `var total = 0;` to look for that code with anything between `var` and `total` and anything between the `0` and the semi-colon

``` diff
- /var\\s*total\\s*=\\s*0\\s*;/
+ /var.*?total\\s*=\\s*0.*?;/
```

I also had to relax the last test that checks for the initialization of `total` equal to `20` to accept commas in the lookaround.

``` diff
- /total[\\s\\+\\-]*=\\s*(\\d(?!\\s*;)|[1-9])/g
+ /total[\\s\\+\\-]*=\\s*(\\d(?!\\s*[;,])|[1-9])/g
```

- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds new functionality)
- [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would change existing functionality)

#### Checklist:

<!-- Go over all points below, and after creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->

<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask in the Help Contributors room linked above. We're here to help! -->
- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [ ] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #XXXX
#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->
- improve wording of instruction
- fix invalid tag
- Fix whitespace in challenge seed
- Prepend semicolon in tail code so that challenge works even if challenge seed or user code doesn't end with a semicolon.
- Improved readability of solution
#### Solution Modification

**Previous Solution**

``` js
function updateRecords(id, prop, value) {
  if(value !== "") {
    if(prop === "tracks") {
      collection[id][prop]= collection[id][prop] || [];
 collection[id][prop].push(value);
    } else {
      collection[id][prop] = value;
    }
  } else {
    delete collection[id][prop];
  }

  return collection;
}
```

**New Solution**

``` js
function updateRecords(id, prop, value) {
  if(value === "") delete collection[id][prop];
  else if(prop === "tracks") {
    collection[id][prop] = collection[id][prop] || [];
    collection[id][prop].push(value);
  } else {
    collection[id][prop] = value;
  }

  return collection;
}
```
#### Screenshot

> [![](http://i.imgur.com/CQ0vTMQ.png)](http://i.imgur.com/CQ0vTMQ.png)
#### Possible Related issues:-
- https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/issues/9168
- https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/issues/7085

---

**If approved, please ask me to squash the changes.**

As these vulnerabilities are now publicly known, attackers can try to use them against your application, making fixing them a matter of urgency.

To help expedite the fix, Snyk created this pull request with the necessary changes to address the vulnerabilities.

This pull request includes:

You can read more about Snyk's upgrade and patch logic in [Snyk's documentation](https://snyk.io/docs/faqs/#fixing-vulnerabilities). Each vulnerability advisory includes information about the vulnerable versions, and direct links to the available patches.

Note that this pull request only addresses the newly disclosed vulnerabilities mentioned above.

See the Snyk [test report](https://snyk.io/test/github/freecodecamp/freecodecamp/HEAD) to review and remediate the full list of vulnerable dependencies.

The Snyk team

Hello lovely humans, [eslint](https://www.npmjs.com/package/eslint) just published its new version 3.1.0.
State Update :rocket:
Dependency eslint
New version 3.1.0
Type dependency
This version is **not covered** by your **current version range**. Without accepting this pull request your project will work just like it did before. There might be a bunch of new features, fixes and perf improvements that the maintainers worked on for you though. I recommend you look into these changes and try to get onto the latest version of eslint. Given that you have a decent test suite, a passing build is a strong indicator that you can take advantage of these changes by merging the proposed change into your project. Otherwise this branch is a great starting point for you to work on the update. Do you have any ideas how I could improve these pull requests? Did I report anything you think isn’t right? Are you unsure about how things are supposed to work? There is a collection of [frequently asked questions](https://greenkeeper.io/faq.html) and while I’m just a bot, there is a group of people who are happy to teach me new things. - [ ] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #XXXX
#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

Calculator project example update:

Previous calculator had several bugs that were addressed. Per Quincy Larson's request, this file has been updated to provide a new calculator example existing under Free Code Camp's CodePen profile that has corrected the following bugs in the previous calculator example:
1. Entry box is now limited so all numbers / operations in use are visible.
2. Corrected the use of operators - now you can not begin with an operator or use an operator twice in a row.
3. Corrected the use of the decimal - now you can only use the decimal once per number to be evaluated.
4. Corrected the use of zero - you now may not begin with or use multiple zeros unless it is in relation to a number with a decimal.
5. Corrected a bug where once you received an answer, you may continue using the answer in another equation.
6. Corrected a Clear Entry (CE) bug where once an equation's answer is returned, it does not All Clear (AC) if 'CE' is clicked.

The following newly disclosed vulnerabilities impact one or more of the npm packages this project uses:
- [npm:minimatch:20160620](https://snyk.io/vuln/npm:minimatch:20160620)

As these vulnerabilities are now publicly known, attackers can try to use them against your application, making fixing them a matter of urgency.

To help expedite the fix, Snyk created this pull request with the necessary changes to address the vulnerabilities.

This pull request includes:
- `package.json` scripts and a Snyk policy (`.snyk`) file, which patch the vulnerabilities that can't be upgraded away.

You can read more about Snyk's upgrade and patch logic in [Snyk's documentation](https://snyk.io/docs/faqs/#fixing-vulnerabilities). Each vulnerability advisory includes information about the vulnerable versions, and direct links to the available patches.

Note that this pull request only addresses the newly disclosed vulnerabilities mentioned above.

See the Snyk [test report](https://snyk.io/test/github/freecodecamp/freecodecamp/HEAD) to review and remediate the full list of vulnerable dependencies.

Please check the changes in this PR to ensure they won't cause issues with your application.

Stay secure,

The Snyk team

- [x] All new and existing tests pass the command `npm run test-challenges`. Use `git commit --amend` to amend any fixes.
#### Type of Change

<!-- What type of change does your code introduce? After creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->
- [ ] Small bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue)
- [x] New feature (non-breaking change which adds new functionality)
- [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would change existing functionality)
- [ ] Add new translation (feature adding new translations)
#### Checklist:

<!-- Go over all points below, and after creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->

<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask in the Help Contributors room linked above. We're here to help! -->
- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [x] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #9905
#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

Here is a brief explanation of the code:
`ALLOWED_METHODS`: we only care about `GET`, this is an array in case we want to add other methods. Can be replaced by a string if you want.
`EXCLUDED_PATHS`: All those are excluded so we don't flash anything. We hit `/api/flyers/findOne` on every page request and this is excluded as well as `/challenges/current-challenge` because those will lead to duplicate flash messages. `/signout` is excluded to not to show a flash message after a cheater logs out.
`req.url !== '/'` is immediately after `req.user` because when a user is logged in `/` redirects to `/challenges/current-challenge` and that redirects to the current challenge. So we get three `GET` requests and thus three flash messages.
Below are some screenshots:
**Cheaters profile page, cheater is not logged in.**
![](http://i.prntscr.com/10d215f97e494585a362b1d57a80ed8b.png)
**Immediately after cheater logged in.**
![](http://i.prntscr.com/57345127e2ee4afeacab18695d807362.png)
**Page `About`**
![](http://i.prntscr.com/79194101b11f4615b60072e6129a6510.png)
**Page `Shop`**
![](http://i.prntscr.com/1f70a8dcd6064ea6b49b9253f6c242e0.png)
**Cheaters profile page, cheater is logged in.**
![](http://i.prntscr.com/1e9cf3eac6464efabddaf78e9e688198.png)
And the same for `Commit` page, setting page and so on.

body:
Hello lovely humans, [gulp-uglify](https://www.npmjs.com/package/gulp-uglify) just published its new version 2.0.0.
State Update :rocket:
Dependency gulp-uglify
New version 2.0.0
Type devDependency
This version is **not covered** by your **current version range**. Without accepting this pull request your project will work just like it did before. There might be a bunch of new features, fixes and perf improvements that the maintainers worked on for you though. I recommend you look into these changes and try to get onto the latest version of gulp-uglify. Given that you have a decent test suite, a passing build is a strong indicator that you can take advantage of these changes by merging the proposed change into your project. Otherwise this branch is a great starting point for you to work on the update. Do you have any ideas how I could improve these pull requests? Did I report anything you think isn’t right? Are you unsure about how things are supposed to work? There is a collection of [frequently asked questions](https://greenkeeper.io/faq.html) and while I’m just a bot, there is a group of people who are happy to teach me new things. [Let them know](https://github.com/greenkeeperio/greenkeeper/issues/new). Good luck with your project :sparkles: You rock! :palm_tree: --- [GitHub Release](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/releases/tag/v2.0.0)

Bug Fixes

  • errors: emit errors of type GulpUglifyError (1232c3c)
  • minifer: use gulplog for the warning (5632cee)

Features

  • minifier: use UglifyJS 2.7.0's input map support (8160697)

BREAKING CHANGES

  • errors: Emitted errors are of a new type. Original UglifyJS error message are preserved instead of the attempt to normalize them. The constructor is exported as "GulpUglifyError" to allow for instance checks.
  • minifier: Now requires UglifyJS 2.7.0 or greater to use the input object support.
--- The new version differs by 35 commits . - [`e4f9045`](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/commit/e4f904509bc4ca5bcfdb84d26d5164a92a637f1e) 2.0.0 - [`566ec6a`](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/commit/566ec6ad1353ea59829cd0700619bf6e3249079d) refactor(tests): write tests with mocha - [`5651111`](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/commit/5651111646c77dd36cc8115dbf56b8f51dcb908d) refactor(tests): replace `cmem` with `testdouble` - [`b82387b`](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/commit/b82387bc3d0892ba11d6214393a08e90fecf20eb) refactor(tests): compose streams with `mississippi` utilities - [`1232c3c`](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/commit/1232c3cc68b5cb3632707ce212ab7fb3f682ff6f) fix(errors): emit errors of type `GulpUglifyError` - [`5632cee`](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/commit/5632ceeb004b971cb57a4723efb33ab7bf9e7cf6) fix(minifer): use `gulplog` for the warning - [`8160697`](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/commit/8160697e39f2f2e295c6f8b6e76215da5c3c4f93) feat(minifier): use UglifyJS 2.7.0's input map support - [`3ec8fc3`](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/commit/3ec8fc3e09da86735904ace581eebb69f5e3891d) chore(package): update uglify-js to version 2.7.0 - [`a9c55b9`](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/commit/a9c55b9e6ff99a8d395fb1e82d0050c11c256483) doc(README): spelling mistake in example - [`80da765`](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/commit/80da765a266cb7ff9d034a73bde0abe18d72d6de) chore(release): 1.5.4 - [`01fb8ca`](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/commit/01fb8caa2c11ae5a8beac222db33d429ba388428) chore(package): update uglify-js to version 2.6.4 - [`8aa877e`](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/commit/8aa877e330cedec9bea0a1ce7d3715417e101714) chore(package): update uglify-js to version 2.6.3 - [`0027093`](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/commit/0027093c124bc425c0a09d3dc6bc4583446e8138) chore(lint): resolve lint failures - [`fe2158a`](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/commit/fe2158a67ed9cdebc62f0e0ea88342b1d16c5ba2) chore(package): update xo to version 0.16.0 - [`a03b663`](https://github.com/terinjokes/gulp-uglify/commit/a03b663d2af229efd4584b15661f2ce457848ee2) docs(README): document how to minify (some) ES6 There are 35 commits in total. #### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

This tests for the possibility that not all source keys have been properly checked against every object contained in the collection.

Previously, this resulted in [a faulty solution](https://repl.it/CLmj/0) (which did not always check all 'source' keys) passing the test. Details can be found where I've [corrected the solution](https://repl.it/CLmj/1): https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/wiki/pull/1246

It has also been referenced in the forum [here](http://forum.freecodecamp.com/t/algorithm-wherefore-art-thou/16092/2?u=sautille)

This PR updates the test case so a faulty solution does not pass all given tests.

body:
The intention of issue #8115 seems to be to consolidate unsubscribe
behaviour. This commit attempts to formalize this by handling all
unsubscribe routes with the same exact handler.

It changes the behaviour of unsubscribe-notifications to be consistent
as discussed in pull request #8135.

This is technically a breaking change, but I'm under the impression that
it's changing into the originally intended behaviour. It's currently a bug.

body:
Due to the nature of stylesheets and font-face tags, we cannot cache them. They requires relative urls to fetch fonts, which if embedded in a style tag, throughs off those urls. When called in using a link tag, that relative url still points to the source of the link tag.

closes #9973

body:
Pulls code in this order

If present in uri (i.e. ?solution=function foo() {}). This will locks the challenge as running untrusted code until the user unlocks it manually.

If present in localStorage
- this checks first for the modern version, which uses the challenge id instead of title with 'Val' appended
- then checks for the legacy version,
  - i.e. 'Concat StringsVal', and converts it to the modern version
  - removes the legacy key

If both of the above find nothing, it then looks at the user challengeMap if available and pulls the previous solution.

When a user completes a challenge, the local copy is removed.

closes #9115
closes #9984
closes #9598
closes #10052

Adjusts tests for challenge "Access MultiDimensional Arrays With Indexes" by checking that a user uses the correct array indices to access the required value (rather than any digit), and that a user does not directly assign to `myData` a number or arithmetic expression.

body:
This commit speeds up the builds by upto 3 times than the current.
It uses npm 3 over npm 2 (travis default), and caches the
dependencies.

This is okay, because our prime two testing areas are, linting and
tests for the challenges.

NOTE: The speed up should happen from the second build,
as it will take at least one build to cache the dependencies.

Just a supporting Screenshot
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1884376/17699143/c3709c48-63dc-11e6-8c43-f61238180828.png)

Perf improvement of about 4 minutes.

- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds new functionality)

- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [x] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #10232 
#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

I changed the directions to the Exact Change challenge, as there was a common misconception users weren't catching about the conditions needed to return "Insufficient Funds." In addition to the existing sentence 

> Return the string "Insufficient Funds" if cash-in-drawer is less than the change due.

, I added this to it: 

> Return the string "Insufficient Funds" if cash-in-drawer is less than the change due or if you cannot return exact change.

to make it clear that if you don't have exact change (not just if you don't have enough money to return the change requested) you need to return "Insufficient Funds."

The Open Weather Map API was not serving over HTTPS, leading to mixed content issues, since geolocation requires HTTPS. Forecast.io's API is also free, requires sign up, but up to 1k hits per day w/ no charge or card on file.

I'm (unsurprisingly) not the first person to notice this. Seems to intersect w/ #7853 and #9145, the latter I believe it closes, at least accounts for it from the documentation side of things (as the currently recommended open weather map API leads to a funny experience, at least for Chrome users).

Hello lovely humans, [eslint-plugin-react](https://www.npmjs.com/package/eslint-plugin-react) just published its new version 6.2.0.
State Update :rocket:
Dependency eslint-plugin-react
New version 6.2.0
Type devDependency
This version is **not covered** by your **current version range**. Without accepting this pull request your project will work just like it did before. There might be a bunch of new features, fixes and perf improvements that the maintainers worked on for you though. I recommend you look into these changes and try to get onto the latest version of eslint-plugin-react. Given that you have a decent test suite, a passing build is a strong indicator that you can take advantage of these changes by merging the proposed change into your project. Otherwise this branch is a great starting point for you to work on the update. Do you have any ideas how I could improve these pull requests? Did I report anything you think isn’t right? Are you unsure about how things are supposed to work? There is a collection of [frequently asked questions](https://greenkeeper.io/faq.html) and while I’m just a bot, there is a group of people who are happy to teach me new things. [Let them know](https://github.com/greenkeeperio/greenkeeper/issues/new). Good luck with your project :sparkles: You rock! :palm_tree: --- [GitHub Release](https://github.com/yannickcr/eslint-plugin-react/releases/tag/v6.2.0)

Added

  • Adds no-unused-prop-types rule (#226 @EvNaverniouk)
  • Add style-prop-object rule (#715 @petersendidit)
  • Add auto fix for self-closing-comp (#770 @pl12133)
  • Add support for typeAnnotations in sort-comp (#235 @dozoisch)
  • Add support for PureComponent in prefer-stateless-function (#781 @tiemevanveen)

Fixed

  • Fix jsx-uses-vars to work better with prefer-const. You'll need to upgrade to ESLint 3.4.0 to completely fix the compatibility issue (#716)
  • Fix require-render-return crash (#784)
  • Fix related components detection in prop-types (#735)
  • Fix component detection to ignore functions expression without a parent component

Changed

  • Update dependencies
  • Documentation improvements (@lencioni)
--- The new version differs by 142 commits . - [`80fd8e1`](https://github.com/yannickcr/eslint-plugin-react/commit/80fd8e16c1640626ed694f78166f03d19208b366) Update CHANGELOG and bump version - [`953e858`](https://github.com/yannickcr/eslint-plugin-react/commit/953e858ce7d7e07d4366fa6b8dde79092abc3cb0) Add test to check jsx-uses-vars and prefer-const compatibility (#716) - [`33a3516`](https://github.com/yannickcr/eslint-plugin-react/commit/33a35163bf5b49e6172bbc9271eef0a31e21f3e7) Update dependencies - [`ed1f168`](https://github.com/yannickcr/eslint-plugin-react/commit/ed1f168132c125fa596e71adf6d3926adc2691dd) Adds no-unused-prop-types rule (fixes #226) - [`466bb5e`](https://github.com/yannickcr/eslint-plugin-react/commit/466bb5ecfcc80b107b7b6dc5686e91f3674f08b9) Fix require-render-return crash (fixes #784) - [`7024678`](https://github.com/yannickcr/eslint-plugin-react/commit/7024678853b5e2650ccf9c1df33d20e2120b6450) Add PureComponent support to prefer-stateless-function - [`d4dee48`](https://github.com/yannickcr/eslint-plugin-react/commit/d4dee487b92aebe7377a38cb6493c44ebc3569b8) Fix jsx-uses-vars to work better with prefer-const (fixes #716) - [`70bf28d`](https://github.com/yannickcr/eslint-plugin-react/commit/70bf28d89eae53b53e3bf41c4bae84cb8700f984) Fix component detection to ignore functions expression without a parent component -   :white_check_mark: Three relevant commits (separate)

#### Type of Change

<!-- What type of change does your code introduce? After creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->

#### Checklist:

<!-- Go over all points below, and after creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->

<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask in the Help Contributors room linked above. We're here to help! -->
- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [x] closes https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/issues/10456 by adding some instructions i.e.  

>  The resulting array must contain only unique values (_no duplicates_).
#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->
- Add tests which would make creating solutions easier by looking at tests.
- Refactor previous solution to use a declarative solution (_functional programming paradigm_).

**Updated Solution**  

``` js
function sym() {
  var arrays = [].slice.call(arguments);
  return arrays.reduce(function (symDiff, arr) {
    return symDiff.concat(arr).filter(function (val, idx, theArr) {
      return theArr.indexOf(val) === idx 
        && (symDiff.indexOf(val) === -1 || arr.indexOf(val) === -1);
    });
  });
}
sym([1, 2, 3], [5, 2, 1, 4]);
```

**Previous Solution**  

``` js
function sym(args) {
  var index = -1;
  var length = arguments.length;
  var result;
  while (++index < length) {
    var array = arguments[index];
    result = result ? diff(result, array).concat(diff(array, result)) : array;
  }
  return result ? uniq(result) : [];
}

function uniq(arr) {
  var h = Object.create(null);
  var u = [];
  arr.forEach(function(v) {
    if (v in h) return;
    h[v] = true;
    u.push(v);
  });
  return u;
}

function diff(a, b) {
  var h = Object.create(null);
  b.forEach(function(v) {
    h[v] = true;  
  });
  return a.filter(function(v) { return !(v in h);});
}
sym([1, 2, 3], [5, 2, 1, 4]);

```

body:
Hello lovely humans, [react-fontawesome](https://www.npmjs.com/package/react-fontawesome) just published its new version 1.2.0.
State Update :rocket:
Dependency react-fontawesome
New version 1.2.0
Type dependency
This version is **not covered** by your **current version range**. Without accepting this pull request your project will work just like it did before. There might be a bunch of new features, fixes and perf improvements that the maintainers worked on for you though. I recommend you look into these changes and try to get onto the latest version of react-fontawesome. Given that you have a decent test suite, a passing build is a strong indicator that you can take advantage of these changes by merging the proposed change into your project. Otherwise this branch is a great starting point for you to work on the update. Do you have any ideas how I could improve these pull requests? Did I report anything you think isn’t right? Are you unsure about how things are supposed to work? There is a collection of [frequently asked questions](https://greenkeeper.io/faq.html) and while I’m just a bot, there is a group of people who are happy to teach me new things. [Let them know](https://github.com/greenkeeperio/greenkeeper/issues/new). Good luck with your project :sparkles: You rock! :palm_tree: --- The new version differs by 23 commits . - [`2fcd4d7`](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/commit/2fcd4d70cc82bdbc4f65738e83cce19deb26d7fa) 1.2.0 - [`68d9c07`](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/commit/68d9c0700ae8572320c128e60844abf6a7846a58) Simplify class creation code, cleanup test suite. - [`6be1726`](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/commit/6be17263175cc22f6e1f169107bdc74440c402f0) Merge pull request #21 from callumsmits/master - [`f27324f`](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/commit/f27324f6f4c9635a5107b837aeb1eb83dc8165d2) Append className prop as a string - [`2997901`](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/commit/2997901c8fc1e0d6faedfbf8feb35e7b95d923bd) Add option to pass FontAwesome as css module - [`0a22f32`](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/commit/0a22f32a52b17c4d0f73f30a5aa79946ee123de4) Update changelog ☺️ - [`add7fd3`](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/commit/add7fd3747b3b3c2377cfe488d992a946e987bc8) 1.1.0 - [`07cdaac`](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/commit/07cdaac7c08598cf834e171b60cf1dfed01fd187) Remove prepublish so module works on windows. - [`abaae44`](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/commit/abaae44729404ee8b2d1b39308feeda6f2f85480) 1.0.0 - [`ec7dc15`](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/commit/ec7dc1548102daebca773c49bb17295d4177781e) Whitespace - [`6927d12`](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/commit/6927d128373ca0b4450237b051434deeff952ed1) Fix React DOM warning. - [`2845a2a`](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/commit/2845a2ad6d827149a28df7dbba06276d9a7213df) Have Travis test iojs, Node 4 and Node 5 - [`76fbede`](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/commit/76fbede1ebe7915faff5679fdf363e4ec7f31dd9) Bump node version. - [`e34dbf4`](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/commit/e34dbf4da25c6dfb9f2770bc47f57ee4cc897c95) Merge pull request #8 from ide/remove-extraneous-props - [`1c8f7ee`](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/commit/1c8f7ee7bb4128222fc265eb96f0ad64bd322ddb) [Tests] Use latest Node instead of latest io.js There are 23 commits in total. See the [full diff](https://github.com/danawoodman/react-fontawesome/compare/f91701d16a57337657c1e027ac5f6bd9cb932f43...2fcd4d70cc82bdbc4f65738e83cce19deb26d7fa). --- This pull request was created by [greenkeeper.io](https://greenkeeper.io/). Note that some vulnerabilities couldn’t be fully fixed and weren’t explicitly ignored, and so will still fail the Snyk test report.

Check the changes in this PR to ensure they won't cause issues with your project.

#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

An issue with `min-width: 1%` seemed to be causing the button issue so I changed that to `inherit`. And an attribute of `overflow-y: auto;` was making the triple scroll bar issue on Firefox (and Chrome in my experience) so I removed these. I've tested on Mac Chrome, Firefox, and Safari and changed the display size and these changes don't seem to affect anything else negatively. I haven't tested on Windows FF or IE.

As for deleting the search bar in FF, I added a `e.preventDefault()` that got it working. Took way too long to figure out it was something so simple...

#### Description

The regex now accounts for the error encountered by user where `Math.random() * 100` was considered a valid entry.
This is my first PR into FreeCodeCamp's repo, so would appreciate any feedback. I've also got a question/suggestion and a comment:

**Question/suggestion:**
I've looked through the code and couldn't find where this is being tested with a negative expectation. E.g. `100` should _not_ pass. The lack of such tests are the reason this bug occurred, imo, and it would be great to have some safe guards against it.

So, something like this could be possible:

```
"solutions": [
  "var randomNumberBetween0and19 = Math.floor(Math.random() * 20);\nfunction randomWholeNum() {\n  return Math.floor(Math.random() * 10);\n}"
],
"failingExamples": [
  "var randomNumberBetween0and19 = Math.floor(Math.random() * 20);\nfunction randomWholeNum() {\n  return Math.floor(Math.random() * 100);\n}"
]
```

If I have not noticed where it is already implemented, my apologies in advance!

**Comment**
I just wanted to say that the setup instructions that you provided and ease of setup are really awesome. Maybe I was lucky this time, but I literally spent just 15 minutes setting the whole project up locally, and I'm not even a node pro! 👏

#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

Challenge: "Add Different Margins to Each Side of an Element"
Change the order tests are run to Top, Right, Bottom, Left.
Previous they were ordered as Top, Left, Right, Bottom.

Why: The Tests, in the order run, form a checklist of the items the student needs to perform in order to pass this challenge.
The order they were listed is not only unnatural, but is not the order they need to memorize and write their code in later.
Reordering the tests to the proper Top, Right, Bottom, Left format prepares them to think, and act in that order and aids in future memorization of the sequence.
