- [x] All new and existing tests pass the command `npm run test-challenges`. Use `git commit --amend` to amend any fixes.
#### Type of Change

<!-- What type of change does your code introduce? After creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->
- [x] Small bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue)
- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds new functionality)
- [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would change existing functionality)
- [ ] Add new translation (feature adding new translations)
#### Checklist:

<!-- Go over all points below, and after creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->

<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask in the Help Contributors room linked above. We're here to help! -->
- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [ ] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #XXXX
#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

I've started contributing to FreeCodeCamp about a week ago. When I started contributing, I also joined the Contributors chat room. From my own experience and the experience of many other new contributors, I've found there's an issue in the `npm run only-once` command. `\n` on Windows doesn't add a new line. In fact, it's even worse. In the script, it seems to break. This pull request removes the new lines. I realize that this does make these little messages harder to catch. I think the trade-off is worth it, though. Because there is no new output for a while after the first message, and the last message is the very last thing logged, they're still hard to miss. I did some research on getting newlines in the command line on Windows, but there doesn't seem to be an easy cross-platform solution.  
I hope this will help out new contributors, taking one more bump out of the road of contributing to a large open source project. 🔥
name: freeCodeCamp

#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

Changing 'because' to 'and' alters the sense of the sentence "These conditions are known as `Boolean` conditions because [and] they may only be true or false." "Because" implies that the name `boolean` inherently implies truthiness or falsiness, which is not the case, and even if it has come to have that association for developers and mathematicians, new programming students with no development or mathematical background would not make that association.

In [/client/saga/err-saga.js#7](https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/blob/staging/client/sagas/err-saga.js#L7), the dispatched action has type `app.makeToast` but there is no this type name in the project. I looked into [/common/app/redux/types.js](https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/blob/staging/common/app/redux/types.js) which contains all the action types with prefix `app`, and `makeToast` is no where to be found. So I use the action creator from [/common/app/toasts/redux/actions.js](https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/blob/staging/common/app/toasts/redux/actions.js) instead.

closes #11198

- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [ ] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #XXXX
#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

Part one of fixing `npm test` on Windows (#10885). By replacing `jsonlint` with `jsonlint-cli` (as suggested by @BerkeleyTrue) we fix the json linting on Windows. `jsonlint` was failing because it doesn't handle glob paths (paths with a \* in them). This is one of the main things mentioned by `jsonlint-cli`, it seems we're not the only ones with this issue 😄
The `-q` option is removed. `jsonlint-cli` does not support this option, rather it doesn't log anything by default as long as there are no errors.
name: freeCodeCamp

#### Description

<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

Part 2/2 of fixing the test suite on Windows (#10885). 
For some reason, the single quotes trip Windows out. It errors without explanation. Using escaped double quotes fixes this issue.
Combined with #11407, this fixes the full test suite on Windows (I now need to wait a lot longer than running just `npm run test-challenges` 😄 ). [I made a new branch](https://github.com/systimotic/FreeCodeCamp/tree/fix/full-test) in my fork where you can check out the combined changes. When both of these fixes are merged, #10885 and #10888 can be continued.

#### Checklist:
<!-- Go over all points below, and after creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->

- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [x] Closes currently open issue: https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/issues/11461

#### Description
<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

- Removes bower
- Ports dependencies that were required through Bower to `npm`.
- Ads CDNs for CSS files

Some thoughts on future improvements (would love to hear what you guys think about these!):
- Replace `npm` with `yarn`
  - Super easy transition, for most cases
- Remove CDNs for libraries like `font-awesome`, `codemirror` and `bootstrap`. These can be loaded and served by webpack.
  - Right now CDNs for `font-awesome` alone are in 12+ places. And require two different versions, I can imagine that's not ideal to manage.

Appreciate review and any feedback/comments. Thanks!!

Hello lovely humans, [history](https://www.npmjs.com/package/history) just published its new version 4.4.0.
State Update :rocket:
Dependency history
New version 4.4.0
Type dependency
This version is **not covered** by your **current version range**. Without accepting this pull request your project will work just like it did before. There might be a bunch of new features, fixes and perf improvements that the maintainers worked on for you though. I recommend you look into these changes and try to get onto the latest version of history. Given that you have a decent test suite, a passing build is a strong indicator that you can take advantage of these changes by merging the proposed change into your project. Otherwise this branch is a great starting point for you to work on the update. Do you have any ideas how I could improve these pull requests? Did I report anything you think isn’t right? Are you unsure about how things are supposed to work? There is a collection of [frequently asked questions](https://greenkeeper.io/faq.html) and while I’m just a bot, there is a group of people who are happy to teach me new things. [Let them know](https://github.com/greenkeeperio/greenkeeper/issues/new). Good luck with your project :sparkles: You rock! :palm_tree: --- The new version differs by 249 commits . - [`e443454`](https://github.com/mjackson/history/commit/e4434544b8bc621e0cbdeafa6938a6e77b922dd8) Version 4.4.0 - [`2f1e8b6`](https://github.com/mjackson/history/commit/2f1e8b6a2f6abed27c1d1345273119b67daae8b3) Update CHANGES - [`f92194d`](https://github.com/mjackson/history/commit/f92194d5db067484a489c91da84668dd33251423) Updated CHANGES - [`ddaab36`](https://github.com/mjackson/history/commit/ddaab3643544ecc4edea133fd9e3c83f57ef800a) Use value-equal instead of deepEqual (#381) - [`929d5dc`](https://github.com/mjackson/history/commit/929d5dca576512ab698486c98a3cb063e9a17ca9) Rename private method - [`0e07ff0`](https://github.com/mjackson/history/commit/0e07ff0082de93814a1d61a27c4c174b0a7ee118) Remove docs - [`e16b244`](https://github.com/mjackson/history/commit/e16b244cc21a4217f0f21bdbd017790ea7c55eba) Version 4.3.0 - [`d7e9b15`](https://github.com/mjackson/history/commit/d7e9b153e80001d7a2ddadad42cfb30761f1be77) Update CHANGES - [`b559a3b`](https://github.com/mjackson/history/commit/b559a3b31951334f4c230ec898d56e5ddcd6e554) Update CHANGES - [`7c6001c`](https://github.com/mjackson/history/commit/7c6001c2f0e226398e6d7f0fea0918287825200a) More stringent key checking in initial entries - [`445ce3e`](https://github.com/mjackson/history/commit/445ce3ef4c1d3745dfae6eb199ce47b5d9eafadc) Allow relative pathnames - [`264d558`](https://github.com/mjackson/history/commit/264d5580897dee17a0fbfedd28b938ab14c9b0f4) Rename PushBadArgs => PushMissingPathname - [`a62990c`](https://github.com/mjackson/history/commit/a62990cbd226cbff1313b31a5d668bfc250a0444) Version 4.2.1 - [`9443a3f`](https://github.com/mjackson/history/commit/9443a3f2997e9404c559c7a1a4aef655742a96eb) Update CHANGES - [`e07bb3c`](https://github.com/mjackson/history/commit/e07bb3c6509e525edde3469146f60f529993aa67) Minor style tweaks There are 249 commits in total. Hello lovely humans, [babel-core](https://www.npmjs.com/package/babel-core) just published its new version 6.18.1.
State Failing tests :rotating_light:
Dependency babel-core
New version 6.18.1
Type dependency
This version is **covered** by your **current version range** and after updating it in your project **the build went from success to failure**. As babel-core is a direct dependency of this project **this is very likely breaking your project right now**. If other packages depend on you it’s very likely also breaking them. I recommend you give this issue a very high priority. I’m sure you can resolve this :muscle: Of course this could just be a false positive, caused by a flaky test suite, or third parties that are currently broken or unavailable, but that would be another problem I’d recommend working on. Do you have any ideas how I could improve these pull requests? Did I report anything you think isn’t right? Are you unsure about how things are supposed to work? #### Checklist:
<!-- Go over all points below, and after creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->
<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask in the Help Contributors room linked above. We're here to help! -->
- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [x] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #11372 

#### Description
<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->
This PR updates the link to the old [wiki article](https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/wiki/Using-MongoDB-And-Deploying-To-Heroku) on deploying MongoDB to Heroku, which is now deprecated. The new link points to the corresponding article on the [forum](http://forum.freecodecamp.com/t/guide-for-using-mongodb-and-deploying-to-heroku/19347) instead. 

This problem was originally [mentioned](https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/issues/11372#issuecomment-257170744) in #11372. That issue itself has been closed since, as it originally dealt with another problem, that has been resolved through a different PR. 

A few things about this PR - 

1. I did not check the "_PR targets the staging branch_" checkbox because this change already exists in the `staging` branch. I was told to target the `backup/staging` branch instead, as this is (kind of) the production site.

2. The issue where this problem was mentioned in, is already closed. So I just mentioned the issue number in the PR template, I did not create a separate `closes XXXXX` comment, as is the norm.

Thanks!
name: freeCodeCamp

- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds new functionality)
- [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would change existing functionality)

#### Checklist:
<!-- Go over all points below, and after creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->
<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask in the Help Contributors room linked above. We're here to help! -->
- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [ ] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #XXXX

#### Description
<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->
@cmal faced some errors running Free Code Camp, as he shared in [this Gitter message](https://gitter.im/FreeCodeCamp/Contributors?at=582f95d4e712c9a11884ec9c). Today (in my timezone, this is technically the same day 😄), I was installing Free Code Camp with @tearingItUp786, and we faced the same errors. As it now was obvious to me this was definitely not an environment issue or user error, I decided to investigate.
This error prevents all Javascript from loading, which makes it impossible to test out anything you develop.
With the help of @cmal, I found that the cause was in react-hot-loader, and the way it interacts with React. The most recent version of React is `15.4.0`, which is allowed by our package.json (`^15.0.2` takes the most recent `15.x.x`). That had a change that made it incompatible with react-hot-loader version `1.x.x`, which is what we're using.
This change was very recent, and according to Google, more people have struggled with this starting about three days ago.
This is fixed in react-hot-loader v3, but that's still in beta. According to the creator however, it's more stable ([source](https://github.com/gaearon/react-hot-loader/issues/417#issuecomment-260995694)). I decided to try to upgrade to this version and see if things would work. It seems like it does!
I'm not familiar with how the hot reloading used to work. With the current state of things, it's hard for me to find out. From what I can tell, it seems to work as it should, but a thorough test by someone who really knows how this is supposed to work would be much appreciated.
I'm not a fan of using a beta version, but as it's more stable according to the creator, and because currently it just doesn't work completely, I believe that this is the best solution.

I view this bug as quite high priority, as any new contributors can currently not get started.
name: freeCodeCamp

Hello lovely humans, [gulp-sourcemaps](https://www.npmjs.com/package/gulp-sourcemaps) just published its new version 2.2.1.
State Failing tests :rotating_light:
Dependency gulp-sourcemaps
New version 2.2.1
Type devDependency
This version is **covered** by your **current version range** and after updating it in your project **the build went from success to failure**. As gulp-sourcemaps is “only” a devDependency of this project it **might not break production or downstream projects**, but “only” your build or test tools – **preventing new deploys or publishes**. I recommend you give this issue a high priority. I’m sure you can resolve this :muscle: Of course this could just be a false positive, caused by a flaky test suite, or third parties that are currently broken or unavailable, but that would be another problem I’d recommend working on. Do you have any ideas how I could improve these pull requests? Did I report anything you think isn’t right? Are you unsure about how things are supposed to work? There is a collection of [frequently asked questions](https://greenkeeper.io/faq.html) and while I’m just a bot, there is a group of people who are happy to teach me new things. [Let them know](https://github.com/greenkeeperio/greenkeeper/issues/new). Good luck with your project :sparkles: You rock! :palm_tree: --- The new version differs by 40 commits . - [`e207533`](https://github.com/floridoo/gulp-sourcemaps/commit/e2075338f192b4a09caccc3b6fc902efa3bd118d) Bump to 2.2.1 for pre-release - [`ba930bd`](https://github.com/floridoo/gulp-sourcemaps/commit/ba930bd14287ec2e5bee88da4fb2572e4d559da9) Merge branch '1.X' - [`66e6d2a`](https://github.com/floridoo/gulp-sourcemaps/commit/66e6d2a570bda1d7f2d45796eb11d8ea072542a8) Merge pull request #255 from realtymaps/dev/nem/1.X/preExistingSourcemapFlag - #### Pre-Submission Checklist
<!-- Go over all points below, and after creating the PR, tick all the checkboxes that apply. -->
<!-- All points should be verified, otherwise, read the CONTRIBUTING guidelines from above-->
<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask. We're here to help! -->
- [X] Your pull request targets the `staging` branch of FreeCodeCamp.
- [X] Branch starts with either `fix/`, `feature/`, or `translate/` (e.g. `fix/signin-issue`)
- [X] You have only one commit (if not, [squash](http://forum.freecodecamp.com/t/how-to-squash-multiple-commits-into-one-with-git/13231) them into one commit).
- [x] All new and existing tests pass the command `npm test`. Use `git commit --amend` to amend any fixes.

#### Type of Change
<!-- What type of change does your code introduce? After creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->
- [X] Small bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue)
- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds new functionality)
- [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would change existing functionality)
- [ ] Add new translation (feature adding new translations)

#### Checklist:
<!-- Go over all points below, and after creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->
<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask in the Help Contributors room linked above. We're here to help! -->
- [X] Tested changes locally.
- [X] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #11750

#### Description
<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->
I change the line "Fulfill the below user stories" to "Fulfill the following user stories" on all front end and data visualization challenges, to be grammatically correct and to be clearly (and consistent). I didn't touch the back end projects, because they use an entirely different phrasing, and are consistent amongst themselves already.

- [ ] Add new translation (feature adding new translations)

#### Checklist:
<!-- Go over all points below, and after creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->
<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask in the Help Contributors room linked above. We're here to help! -->
- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [ ] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #XXXX

#### Description
<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->
Hello there human!

The other day, I was looking at the CONTRIBUTING.md file, when I noticed a typo! 😱 _I have to fix this!_
After I opened the file, I ended up fixing and tweaking some other things as well. Here's a summary:
- My editor (Atom) automatically removed some trailing spaces
- There was only a single "I" in the entire file. I changed it to be more consistent.
- The Contributors chat room on Gitter is referenced as "Contributors chat room," "Contributors Chat Room" and "Contributors room", sometimes as a link, sometimes not. I edited some cases to be more consistent.
- The "How to find the code in the Free Code Camp codebase to fix/edit?" was in the PR section. I moved it near "Make changes" to hopefully be easier to find and harder to miss.
- With the current state of the project, after making changes to the seed files, you need to run `node seed` for them to be visible. This was never mentioned in this file. I added a section that talks about this. I assume it wasn't there because it previously updated automatically. I hope this helps resolve a common confusion among new contributors.
- Previously, the test section mentioned running a different command on Windows to test. This has been fixed (ref #10885), so I removed that part.
- The linting section mentioned that lines shouldn't be longer than 80 characters because of jsonlint. I'm not sure why or how that ever worked. As the name might suggest, jsonlint only lints the JSON. The linting talked about in this section only lints the .js and .jsx files. There is no maximum line length in the JSON files. I have tested this, it doesn't break. I removed this section because it seemed to be false information. 😅 Apart from that, it seems weird to me to only detail a single rule out of alllll of them.
- These last two are really nitpicking. I fixed the casing on a username. I also switched the order of two items in an unordered list to match the headings that followed it.

I know it's not such a great idea to stuff many different things into a single PR, but once I got started, I couldn't stop myself 😊

Have a great day! 🔥
name: freeCodeCamp

- [ ] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #XXXX

#### Description
<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->
While completing the Friendly Dates challenge, I noticed that none of the test cases ensure that dates in the twenty-thirty range actually end in the correct suffix (ex. 21 should be 21st). In other words, prior to this PR, a camper could write a switch that only targeted number 0-19, which doesn't reflect the requirements of the challenge. I modified one of the tests to account for this.

Hello lovely humans, [babel-istanbul](https://www.npmjs.com/package/babel-istanbul) just published its new version 0.12.1.
State Update :rocket:
Dependency babel-istanbul
New version 0.12.1
Type devDependency
This version is **not covered** by your **current version range**. Without accepting this pull request your project will work just like it did before. There might be a bunch of new features, fixes and perf improvements that the maintainers worked on for you though. I recommend you look into these changes and try to get onto the latest version of babel-istanbul. Given that you have a decent test suite, a passing build is a strong indicator that you can take advantage of these changes by merging the proposed change into your project. Otherwise this branch is a great starting point for you to work on the update. Do you have any ideas how I could improve these pull requests? Did I report anything you think isn’t right? Are you unsure about how things are supposed to work? There is a collection of [frequently asked questions](https://greenkeeper.io/faq.html) and while I’m just a bot, there is a group of people who are happy to teach me new things. This adds a simple email-based mechanism to report profiles for abuse. An email with text from the report is sent to Free Code Camp's support account with the reporter's account in copy. This also adds the reporter's details to the report for follow ups.

Tested locally.

Closes #11891

#### Description
<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->
It's likely for `loopProtect` to break out of `sumFibs(4000000)`, but not any other case. Thus for every other case an array of size `num` is returned and tested by `assert.deepEqual`—which will freeze the browser for large `num`s.

This PR piggybacks off of @marzelin's [comment](https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/FreeCodeCamp/issues/11830#issuecomment-264170612), which suggests comparing the expected and actual results manually with the equality operator.

#### Description
Just adds a docker-compose.yml file.

It allows you to quickly spin up a couple of Node and Mongo containers, 
which might be useful in several scenarios, trying out stuff from scratch
without having to deal with installing MongoDB or cleaning the DB.

It might come in handy for CI/CD testing as well.

Bootstrap with:
```
   docker-compose run --rm server npm install
   docker-compose run --rm server npm run only-once
```

Run with:
```
   docker-compose up
```

#### Description
<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->
It's me again, with another module update + webpack related issue that prevented the bundle from successfully compiling (see #11718 for last time).

This time around, it was an issue with `babel-core` using `debug` improperly, which made things break in a SemVer minor update. A patch was done (https://github.com/visionmedia/debug/issues/389), but we had a module replacement in our webpack config that made things break. This was not restored in the patch.

I changed this replacement plugin to replace with `debug` instead of `debug/browser`, which is the recommended way to use the module. It detects if you're in a browser automatically.

Across all of the modules (this includes the backend), Free Code Camp is dependent on three versions of `debug`: `2.2.0`, `2.3.3` and `2.5.3`. This change should work fine with all of these versions. There are currently three references to `debug/node` in our `node_modules`. One of them is from `babel-core`. 
The other two are in `avj`, a sub-sub-dependency of `eslint`. Interestingly, this module is not dependent on `debug`. The references are in a minified file in the `dist` directory. `eslint` is never processed by webpack, so whatever this module does not matter for this PR.

From what I can tell, everything works fine, but I'm not 100% certain.

@BerkeleyTrue review would be much appreciated 🙂

- [x] Tested changes locally.

#### Description
<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->

Here's my test code:
```js
var hi = 'potato';

function right() {
  return 'wrong';
}

console.log('normal thing');
console.log('// this should not really do what it does, but oh well');
console.log(NaN);
console.log([8, null, 0, NaN, undefined, "", 'text', hi, right]);
console.log(['array', ['nested array', ['nested nested array', undefined]]]);
console.log(right());
console.log({
  property: '1',
  otherProperty: 1,
  'anotherProperty': NaN
});
```
This is what that looks like on the current staging branch
![chrome_2017-01-02_15-23-24](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7262039/21590857/802bd14c-d0ff-11e6-96b8-8a85ecbc1d2a.png)
This is what it looks like after my changes
![chrome_2017-01-02_14-06-49](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7262039/21590858/802bf1e0-d0ff-11e6-86a3-38e638b90093.png)

### Things that work great now
- Strings actually show up as strings
- Previously, `undefined` and `NaN` were converted to `null`. They now stay as is.
- Objects are prettified.
- Arrays get an extra space, like they have in the browser console.

### Things that aren't perfect yet
_Nested arrays are now recursively parsed._
- ~Nested arrays and~ property values are still handled by `JSON.stringify`, so they still have the `NaN` -> `null` issue.
- All strings that start with // are displayed as comments.
- ~The indentation of indented arrays doesn't necessarily have to be this way. I guess it comes down to our preference.~
- If there is a lot of logging output, the performance hit may be too big. This change doesn't affect that a whole lot though. It might be good to not log anything larger than `x`.


~Tests are still broken as per #12305. I ran them with the fix from #12317, and they passed.~ Tests have been fixed

- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds new functionality)

<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask in the Help Contributors room linked above. We're here to help! -->
- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [x] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #9037

#### Description
<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->
Clarification of instructions to better match the test cases. Replace this paragraph, in the original wording:

> If multiple pairs are possible that have the same numeric elements but different indices, return the smallest sum of indices. Once an element has been used, it cannot be reused to pair with another.

Which seemed to suggest that in the test case pairwise([0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1], 1)===10 only the pair of indices {0, 4} should be used, to fit the criterion 'if multiple pairs are possible ... return the smallest sum of indices.' However, the expected behavior of the test is that indices {0, 4} and {1, 5} should both be used.

To reflect that, the paragraph is replaced with:

> You may use multiple pairs that have the same numeric elements but different indices. Each pair should use the lowest possible available indices. Once an element has been used it cannot be reused to pair with another element.

#### Description
<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->
Changed the function call from `findOne()` to `update()` with the `multi` parameter set to `true`. This approach no longer requires the extra step of updating the attributes of the user that was found using the `findOne()` function call. Rather, in one function call, we can update the appropriate attributes of all users that have the same email address. Also, because the update function returns a counter that indicates the number of users that were found, the "Email address not found." error can still be displayed when the counter is equal to zero.

#### Description

Upgrades jquery to 3.1.1 (major version upgrade).

I used [this official guide](https://jquery.com/upgrade-guide/3.0/#breaking-change-load-unload-and-error-removed) to upgrade API. I have tested some of the pages, including some of the challenges. I would be glad to help with more testing if someone who knows the app well can lay out a plan. From reading the upgrade doc, it didn't appear that the repo had a bunch of deprecated API, though.

Notes:
- lightbox2 library throws a warning during bower build that it requires JQuery 2. I let this one go, because [there hasn't been any issues reported](https://github.com/lokesh/lightbox2/issues/525) and JQuery 3 seems to work fine with this library.

- [x] You have only one commit (if not, [squash](http://forum.freecodecamp.com/t/how-to-squash-multiple-commits-into-one-with-git/13231) them into one commit).
- [x] All new and existing tests pass the command `npm test`. Use `git commit --amend` to amend any fixes.

#### Type of Change
<!-- What type of change does your code introduce? After creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->
- [x] Curriculum update - modifying basic DS section
- [ ] Small bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue)
- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds new functionality)
- [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would change existing functionality)
- [ ] Add new translation (feature adding new translations)

#### Checklist:
<!-- Go over all points below, and after creating the PR, tick the checkboxes that apply. -->
<!-- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask in the Help Contributors room linked above. We're here to help! -->
- [x] Tested changes locally.

#### Description
<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->
This is a partial completion of issue #12693 - since there is a lot here, I am going one section at a time - this PR is only for the Array challenges. 

There was a lot to be done here:
- array challenges were put in standard FCC format using:
  - `code` tags for language keywords
  - `dfn` tags for key terms
  - `blockquote`s for examples, etc. 
- Fixed the way the test cases were being displayed by adding `'message: ...`
- Replaced all "Instructions" `h4` headers with `hr` elements as discussed in #12688
- Re-ordered array challenges to match the map laid out in Curriculum Expansion issue [#90](https://github.com/freeCodeCamp/CurriculumExpansion/issues/90#issuecomment-270932804)
- Added Bracket Notation challenge which was missed during seeding
- Refactored Create Complex Multi-Dimensional Arrays challenge & tests
- Other bits and pieces of re-factoring along the way

I've run through all of the Array challenges locally (multiple times) and there are no obvious bugs that I can see. I will continue on addressing #12693 and the remaining Object challenges in another PR.

@HKuz I know you are totally swamped, but if you get the chance, I'd love to hear your thoughts on the Array section!
name: freeCodeCamp

**Round II of previous PR containing many improvements to Advanced Data Structures & Algorithms Challenges:**

- Reorganized challenge sequence and removed repeated challenges.

As described in the issue, the closing backticks for a codeblock are indented, which makes them display as code.
It appears that there's an issue with dedent. I tried adding newlines before it both as lines that were empty in the editor and as `\n`, but it did not help.
I switched the code from dedent to good old string concatenation, which works fine.

body: #### Pre-Submission Checklist - [x] Your pull request targets the `staging` branch of freeCodeCamp. - [x] Branch starts with either `fix/`, `feature/`, or `translate/` (e.g. `fix/signin-issue`) - [x] You have only one commit (if not, [squash](http://forum.freecodecamp.com/t/how-to-squash-multiple-commits-into-one-with-git/13231) them into one commit). - [x] All new and existing tests pass the command `npm test`. Use `git commit --amend` to amend any fixes. #### Type of Change - [x] Small bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue) - [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds new functionality) - [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would change existing functionality) - [ ] Add new translation (feature adding new translations) #### Checklist: - [x] Tested changes locally. - [x] Closes currently open issue: Closes #12865 #### Description The [Quoting Strings with Single Quotes](http://beta.freecodecamp.com/en/challenges/basic-javascript/quoting-strings-with-single-quotes) challenge was affected when `'use-strict'` was added to the comment that is invisible to users. Similar to the issue seen in #12722. This challenge uses a regex to count the quotes in the `code` variable, so `'use strict'` and the `tail` was throwing off the count. Logging `code` looks like this: ``` ``` So there is an additional pair of both `'` and `"`. I tried to just accommodate for this by changing the test to account for the extra quotes, but my guess is that since this comment is not actually generated in nodes test environment, approaching it this way caused running `npm test` to fail. So instead, I created an IIFE that executes within the assert and returns `true` or `false`. It slices `code` down to only the relevant parts then just runs the original regex matches against the new string. I also added `blockquote`s for the examples to be consistent with other challenges and added `Do not change anything else.` to the instructions because we are also testing that the string remains unchanged in the first test but don't explicitly say it anywhere, so if someone does what the tests ask but changes the URL in the string, the tests will fail with an erroneous error message.
name: freeCodeCamp

#### Description
Implements @erictleung's suggested changes from [#9651 (comment)](https://github.com/freeCodeCamp/freeCodeCamp/pull/9651/files#r71084020).

This solves the issue mentioned above, but I'm still not happy with the result. Ideally, campers should be able to add `console.log(timesFive(someNumber))` to test their function and see the result in the simulated console to the left on their screen.

However, it's currently only possible to see this test output when the challenge is freshly loaded from the seed (either by visiting it for the first time or by resetting it). As soon as tests has been run, all that's displayed is 
```txt
// running test
// tests completed
```

I'm open for any suggestions!

Since algorithm challenges aim to help campers practice creating algorithms, we recommended their own solutions over those built into the language. This PR adds a test that prevent the most straight-forward forms of cheating by using `String.repeat()`.

It won't catch all possible ways, but it's better than nothing.

Hello lovely humans, [dedent](https://www.npmjs.com/package/dedent) just published its new version 0.7.0.
State Update :rocket:
Dependency dedent
New version 0.7.0
Type dependency
This version is **not covered** by your **current version range**. Without accepting this pull request your project will work just like it did before. There might be a bunch of new features, fixes and perf improvements that the maintainers worked on for you though. I recommend you look into these changes and try to get onto the latest version of dedent. Given that you have a decent test suite, a passing build is a strong indicator that you can take advantage of these changes by merging the proposed change into your project. Otherwise this branch is a great starting point for you to work on the update. Do you have any ideas how I could improve these pull requests? Did I report anything you think isn’t right? Are you unsure about how things are supposed to work? There is a collection of [frequently asked questions](https://greenkeeper.io/faq.html) and while I’m just a bot, there is a group of people who are happy to teach me new things. [Let them know](https://github.com/greenkeeperio/greenkeeper/issues/new). Good luck with your project :sparkles: You rock! :palm_tree: --- The new version differs by 11 commits (ahead by 11, behind by 1). - [`1cae320`](https://github.com/dmnd/dedent/commit/1cae3207449edba5e6d8588f3670bb03e2ad92a0) :arrow_up: upgrade babel & :fire: remove gulp - [`209fe81`](https://github.com/dmnd/dedent/commit/209fe81069ec303798ee61c728064b54e5bd0e96) :arrow_up: upgrade eslint - [`c055708`](https://github.com/dmnd/dedent/commit/c055708c719aa0ad6454e966a6efee4ddede796f) :arrow_up: upgrade jest - [`8c31ddb`](https://github.com/dmnd/dedent/commit/8c31ddbb4c751c46fd65cbc2e902395a74fa4ff4) Start using yarn - [`4db62af`](https://github.com/dmnd/dedent/commit/4db62af1f87a8bfd26882fa0127c88f5ea60eb07) Merge pull request #9 from phenomnomnominal/master - [`03b5b0a`](https://github.com/dmnd/dedent/commit/03b5b0ac879d258d5ecd4a5e1b517db25ea8a1be) Actually build the dist version - [`6508644`](https://github.com/dmnd/dedent/commit/650864440085df20fd4dce391ca697ab40ea2811) Merge remote-tracking branch 'dmnd/master' - [`fa9809d`](https://github.com/dmnd/dedent/commit/fa9809d69687a251c253bbe91a8477a6c27f5049) Merge remote-tracking branch 'dmnd/master' - [`b0d0c4c`](https://github.com/dmnd/dedent/commit/b0d0c4cc585eecb876b306653cd731fe5476c3b0) Fix #8 - [`57b91c1`](https://github.com/dmnd/dedent/commit/57b91c1d6b1ef81976ef9ff7ca9fea41073d923e) Merge pull request #7 from phenomnomnominal/patch-1 - [`f81ff41`](https://github.com/dmnd/dedent/commit/f81ff41b29a8d8ac7f6034c23f5bd1814ba51280) Fixed a bug in the example :) See the [full diff](https://github.com/dmnd/dedent/compare/e7d0bcea425ff647791a30cd9db0fb486c26078a...1cae3207449edba5e6d8588f3670bb03e2ad92a0). --- | ✨ Try the all new [Greenkeeper GitHub Integration](https://git.io/uptodate) ✨ | | --- | | With [Integrations](https://developer.github.com/early-access/integrations/) **first-class bot support** landed on GitHub and we’ve rewritten Greenkeeper to take full advantage of it. **Simpler setup, fewer pull-requests, faster than ever**.

```js
.text((d) =>  (d[0] + 
 + d[1]))
```

```js
.text((d) =>  (d[0] + ", "
 + d[1]))
```
![screen shot 2017-02-01 at 07 46 38](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/18746599/22511479/10a8837c-e853-11e6-9cd4-1278c6d446e4.png)

Now x and y data points displayed as text are separated by a comma.

- [x] Tested changes locally.

#### Description
<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->
This PR is a partial completion of issue #12472.

This mainly targets `seed` files, but I ran a search when I was finished with that directory and found a couple of nagging left over little buggers in other areas of the codebase, so I went ahead and fixed those as well.

I've replaced every instance (visible to the user) of `Free Code Camp`, `free code camp`, `FreeCodeCamp`, `freecodecamp`, and `FREE CODE CAMP` with the much more highly desirable `freeCodeCamp` - except in irrelevant URLs not visible to the user or where required by challenges (ex. regex challenges include other cases in  tests). I did hit some URLs (only the ones that we've changed, i.e. github, codepen), and, I even got the issue template! 

I did mention in #12472 that I did leave a few instances of `freecodecamp` in the Twitch challenge, because not sure how the API would interpret the case change. Also, our name has not yet been changed on Twitch, and we may have left that out of the change plan (looks like we're still FreeCodeCampin' over there! 😜  ).

Anyway, one step closer to putting this issue to rest finally!
name: freeCodeCamp

Correct answer was causing a failure in Safari due to precision error. Used Assert.approximately() to fix issue. Confirmed correct answer now passes in both Safari and Chrome. Before in Safari (Correct answer does not pass): After in Safari (Correct answer passes): After in Chrome (Correct answer still passes): NOTE: Original issue was observed in Mozilla, which turned out to be a different issue that might be resolved once other merges in the pipeline happen. This pull request is addressing the issue with Safari only, as decided in the issue conversation. See conversation in issue #13014 for more detail.

#### Description
<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->
Prevent campers from using the built in `Object.keys()`, since the purpose of the challenge is to use `for...in` combined with `Object.hasOwnProperty()`, to understand what own properties mean, and how to handle them.

**Note:** Breaking change, since it prevents use of `Object.keys()`, which was a valid solution before.

- [x] Tested changes locally.
- [x] Closes currently open issue (replace XXXX with an issue no): Closes #13025

#### Description
<!-- Describe your changes in detail -->
Rewrote the challengeSeed for the "Compare Scopes of the var and let Keywords" ES6 challenge to:
* Reduce the complexity of the challenge, which better highlights the different scopes assigned to the variables declared with `var` or `let`.
* Avoid the dubious coding practice of defining a function within a for loop and the associated linting error in the challenge's code.

Additional Changes:
* Expanded the "note" section to include a statement saying that in your own programs its probably best to use different names for the variables to avoid confusion.
* Added test case placeholders. These will need to be addressed in the future once transpiling issues are resolved.
* Very slight rewording of instructions.

As the OP points out in their issue, using the `i` flag shouldn't really matter much when the regex is `\w`. I made a [JS Bin demo](https://jsbin.com/toheje/edit?js,console) with all the test cases using only the `\g` flag, and all the tests returned the expected results. So, the `i` flag requirement could probably be dropped.

Tested locally - challenge passes without `i` flag -
